    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e6a84b2331f02d6b2d6d7afa5c1ceda7?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 2560357,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2221461,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2221461/raptordotcpp",
                "reputation": 1475,
                "display_name": "RaptorDotCpp",
                "accept_rate": 84
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 5,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1375945091,
            "creation_date": 1375945091,
            "body": "<p>Java requires you to initialize the local variable as a safety measure. It stops you from accidently reading an odd value. If the compiler didn't complain and you were to read the value of x, it could be anything.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 18119750,
            "question_id": 18119705
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/wI1C3.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 48586,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 144424,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/144424/adriaan-stander",
                "reputation": 167094,
                "display_name": "Adriaan Stander",
                "accept_rate": 36
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1375945076,
            "creation_date": 1375945076,
            "body": "<p>Well, the thing is that <code>args[0]<\/code> might be <code>null<\/code>, and then <code>x<\/code> would not be initialized before use. That is why the compiler is complaining at you.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 18119745,
            "question_id": 18119705
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/TCZXp.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 1437744,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1358761,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1358761/ajay-bhojak",
                "reputation": 1159,
                "display_name": "Ajay Bhojak",
                "accept_rate": 60
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1375947283,
            "creation_date": 1375947283,
            "body": "<p>When you don't pass argument then String[] array has nothing and is uninitialized. so the if condition will not be true in this case and even it will throw Exception in thread \"main\" <strong>java.lang.ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException: 0.<\/strong>. Now <strong>assume<\/strong> you have set args[0] to null value at some place in your code then the if(args[0]) != null) will evaluate to false . In that case you are assigning <strong>int y= x;<\/strong> where x is uninitialized. <strong>And I think you should know compiler takes these things into account<\/strong>. <strong>In java you can not use a local variable until it is initialized.<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>That's why the smart Java compiler gives you compile time error and tell you code properly.<\/p>\n\n<p>:-). Hope you got it.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 18120396,
            "question_id": 18119705
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/ynawq.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 2519746,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2190336,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2190336/prabhaker-a",
                "reputation": 8513,
                "display_name": "Prabhaker A"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1375945263,
            "creation_date": 1375945263,
            "body": "<p><b>According to java Local variables must be initialized before use.<\/b><br>\nin your case you are trying to initialize it in condition.Conditions never guaranteed to executes(In run time it may executes or may not execute based on the condition) and trying to assign to <code>y<\/code> variable.<br>\nSo compiler warns about it.  <\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 18119802,
            "question_id": 18119705
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/3Ot5P.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 2485637,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2164109,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2164109/morgano",
                "reputation": 17470,
                "display_name": "morgano"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1375945098,
            "creation_date": 1375945098,
            "body": "<p>Because of performance issues among others, Java doesn't initialize automatically local variables. so here:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code> int x;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>x still have an undefined value. Compiler won't allow you to compile the code because you are referring to <code>x<\/code> in this line:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>int y = x;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>It works in the second case because you are initializing <code>x<\/code> before it is referred elsewehere.<\/p>\n\n<p>Granted, you are initializing <code>x<\/code> inside the <code>if<\/code> statement, but obviously it could be the case that your <code>if<\/code> evaluates to <code>false<\/code>, so the compiler takes that into account.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 18119752,
            "question_id": 18119705
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/buvFz.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 2678195,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2314073,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2314073/juned-ahsan",
                "reputation": 68865,
                "display_name": "Juned Ahsan",
                "accept_rate": 56
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1375945114,
            "creation_date": 1375945114,
            "body": "<blockquote>\n  <p>int y = x; // the compiler will choke here<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Because in case your <code>if<\/code> block does not execute(when arg[0] ==null) then x will not be initialized. Java compiler mandates the variable to be initialized before they can be used.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 18119756,
            "question_id": 18119705
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/38231f4cdaa9009d5d31c6b82012008c?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 2437666,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2127129,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2127129/xiode",
                "reputation": 1,
                "display_name": "Xiode"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": -1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1375945795,
            "creation_date": 1375945795,
            "body": "<p>You're <strong>declaring x as space to hold an integer<\/strong>, but since you didn't give it any integer to hold, <strong>it is still null<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n<p>The compiler looks at both the true and false paths of your if statement. If arg[0] contains something, then you're fine. Otherwise, when you try to set y = x, x has nothing to give to y and you get an error.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 18119952,
            "question_id": 18119705
        }
    ],
